On March 18, 2026, Navigate360 learned that 8.3 million anonymous tips had been exposed. The company&#8217;s response—and the silence of the programs that depend on its platform—has persisted for months. We&#8217;re now seeking accountability through state and federal regulators. A DataBreaches.net Editorial In March 2026, the world learned that a hacktivist had acquired 8.3 million...<img alt="" height="0" src="https://databreaches.net/wp-content/plugins/wp-piwik/proxy/matomo.php?idsite=11&amp;rec=1&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fdatabreaches.net%2F2026%2F07%2F20%2Fbroken-promises-of-anonymity-four-months-later-still-no-transparency-now-were-seeking-accountability%2F%3Fpk_campaign%3Dfeed%26pk_kwd%3Dbroken-promises-of-anonymity-four-months-later-still-no-transparency-now-were-seeking-accountability&amp;action_name=Broken%20Promises%20of%20Anonymity%3A%20Four%20Months%20Later%2C%20Still%20No%20Transparency.%20Now%20We%26%238217%3Bre%20Seeking%20Accountability.&amp;urlref=https%3A%2F%2Fdatabreaches.net%2Ffeed%2F" style="border: 0; width: 0; height: 0;" width="0" />
